quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to compose a valid for loop:
[!raw!]
var i = 1;
{0} (k=1; k<10{1} k++) {2}
   i += k;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The For Loop[/h1]

The example below creates a [b]for [/b]loop that prints numbers 1 through 5.[code format="js" codeId="667"]for ([b]i=1[/b]; [b]i<=5[/b];[b] i++[/b]) {
   document.write(i + "<br />");
}[/code]
In this example, [b]Statement 1[/b] sets a variable before the loop starts (var i = 1).
[b]Statement 2[/b] defines the condition for the loop to run (i must be less than or equal to 5).
[b]Statement 3[/b] increases a value (i++) each time the code block in the loop has been executed.

[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2755" width="100%"]
[b]Statement 1[/b] is optional, and can be omitted, if your values are set before the loop starts.[code format="js" codeId="668"]var i = 1;
for (; i<=5; i++) {
   document.write(i + "<br />");
}[/code]
Also, you can initiate more than one value in [b]statement 1[/b], using [b]commas [/b]to separate them.[code format="js" codeId="669"]for ([b]i=1, text=""[/b]; i<=5; i++) {
   text = i;
   document.write(i + "<br />");
}[/code]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print EVEN values from 0 to 20 using a for loop:
[!raw!]
var x = 0;
for (; x <= {0}; x += {1}) {
   document.write(x); 
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The For Loop [/h1]

If [b]statement 2[/b] returns true, the loop will start over again, if it returns false, the loop will end.
Statement 2 is also optional.
[note]If you omit statement 2, you must provide a [b]break [/b]inside the loop. Otherwise, the loop will never end.[/note]
[b]Statement 3[/b] is used to change the initial variable. It can do anything, including negative increment (i--), positive increment (i = i + 15), or anything else.
Statement 3 is also optional, and it can be omitted if you increment your values inside the loop. [code format="js" codeId="670"]var i = 0;
for (; i < 10; ) {
   document.write(i);
   i++;
}[/code]
